\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
The generator, while running, creates too much heat.
 Thus, a cooling process is imperative.
 Five seconds after the generators operate, a closed cycle of heat dissipation
 takes place.
 Specifically, a pump continuously pushes the water in a tank flowing through
 the generator engine, where it absorbs the heat and becomes hot water.
 Then, hot water is conducted to the fan that blows the heat to cool down
 it before returning to the tank.
 And from here, cool water is again pumped to cool down the generator engine.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\,$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
